I have now done, after I have (which is I think due) given the Reader, and the Author a short account how I came to write this Book, and in this manner. First of all, I was offended at the presumption and arrogance of his stile; whereas there is nothing either of Wit, or Eloquence in all his Books, worthy of a Readers, and more unfit for his own, taking notice of, Then his infinite Tautology was bur •… ensome, which seem'd like marching a Company round a Hill upon a pay-day so often, till if the Muster master were not attentive, they might r •… ceive the pay of a Regim •… nt. All the variety of his Treat is Pork (he knows the story) but so little disguised by good Cookery, that it discovers the miserableness; or rather the penury of the Host. When I observed how he inveighs against the Trading part of the Nation, I thought he deserved to be within the five mile Act, and not to come within that distance of any Corporation. I could not patiently see how irrevorently he treated Kings and P •… inces, as if they had been no better then King Phys and King Ush of B •… anford I thought his profanation of the Scripture intolerable; For though he alledges that 'tis only in order to shew
